    <article class="ks-article">
      <h1 class="ks-title">A Different Way to Keep Score</h1>

      <div class="ks-body">

        <p>Here's a thing that happens. You're standing in front of a painting—or you've just finished one—and something is either happening or it isn't. A pull. A restlessness. Or just nothing: the work sitting there, inert.</p>

        <p>And the language that comes back to you, from critics or teachers or your own internal monologue, is always about meaning. What the work represents. What the artist intended. What it says about the culture or the moment or the painter's biography.</p>

        <p>That language can't tell you why something stopped you cold. It can't tell you why something that should be working isn't. Those aren't interpretation problems. They're visual problems—perceptual problems—happening at a level below meaning, before anyone has decided what the work is about.</p>

        <p>Art Lab starts earlier in that sequence. Upload an image—yours, someone else's, something you photographed and couldn't shake—and what comes back is a read of the observable mechanics. Where attention goes first, and why. What's creating tension and what's releasing it. Which decisions are doing the work and which ones are coasting.</p>

        <p>It doesn't tell you what the painting means. It shows you what it's doing.</p>

        <hr class="ks-rule" />

        <p>The art world measures success by price and placement. Which galleries, which critics, which biennials. Art Lab runs on a different measure: whether someone stops in front of your work long enough for something to happen to them.</p>

        <p>That's not random. It's not taste. It comes down to specific, nameable visual decisions—decisions that land on the nervous system before the viewer has formed a single thought about the work. Before meaning. Before judgment. Before they've decided whether they're the kind of person who gets art.</p>

        <p>Those decisions are learnable. That's what this is for.</p>

      </div>

